[[File:Tedikara no himaturi natu 3.JPG|thumb|240px|Tejikara Fire Festival - Summer (Mikoshi dancing amidst waterfall fireworks)]] [[File:Tedikara no himaturi natu 1.JPG|thumb|240px|Tejikara Fire Festival - Summer (Mikoshi emitting flames)]] [[File:Tedikara no himaturi natu 2.JPG|thumb|240px|Tejikara Fire Festival - Summer (Naked men dancing amidst handheld fireworks)]] [[File:Tedikara no himaturi natu 4.JPG|thumb|240px|Tejikara Fire Festival - Summer (Ground-splitting fireworks)]]
'''Tejikara Fire Festival''' (手力の火祭, Tejikara no Himatsuri) is a {{ill|fire festival|ja|火祭り|12=draft|12=draft}} held at {{ill|Tejikarao Shrine|ja|手力雄神社 (岐阜市)|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Gifu City|ja|岐阜市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Gifu Prefecture|ja|岐阜県|12=draft|12=draft}}. While its origins are unclear, records from the Meiwa era (1760s) indicate its long-standing history. It is a traditional event representative of Gifu City and has been designated an Intangible Folk Cultural Property of Gifu Prefecture.<ref>{{Cite web|ja|date= |url=http://www.pref.gifu.lg.jp/kyoiku-bunka-sports/bunka-geijutsu/bunkazai-zuroku/bunkazai-zuroku/mumin/gifusi/tejikarahimaturi.html |title=手力雄神社火祭り |publisher=岐阜県 |accessdate=2013-04-20}}</ref>
== Overview == After the shrine's 20-meter-high {{ill|sacred lantern|ja|御神灯|12=draft|12=draft}} is successively lit, a waterfall firework display is ignited. The sound of firecrackers reverberates through the shrine grounds, while fiery sparks rain down. Amidst the spectacular firework displays, a mikoshi (portable shrine) rigged with fireworks is carried and danced around by naked men. Highlights include {{ill|handheld fireworks|ja|手筒花火|12=draft|12=draft}}, ground-level firework explosions, and mountain-burning fire displays that leave spectators in awe. There are two events: the "'''Main Festival'''," held in April, and "'''Summer'''," a revived version for tourism purposes held in August. Typically, the term "Main Festival" refers to the April event.
== Main Festival == The '''Main Festival''' is the spring grand festival of {{ill|Tejikarao Shrine|ja|手力雄神社 (岐阜市)|12=draft|12=draft}}. * '''Date:''' Second Saturday of April each year * '''Location:''' {{ill|Tejikarao Shrine (Gifu)|ja|手力雄神社|12=draft|12=draft}} (6-8-22 Kuramae, Gifu City, Gifu Prefecture) * '''Access:''' From {{ill|Meitetsu Gifu Station|ja|名鉄岐阜駅|12=draft|12=draft}}, take the {{ill|Meitetsu Kakamigahara Line|ja|名鉄各務原線|12=draft|12=draft}} to {{ill|Tejikara Station|ja|手力駅|12=draft|12=draft}}, then walk 5 minutes.
== Summer == The '''Summer''' event is a tourism-oriented revival of the festival. Participating neighborhood associations are fewer than in the Main Festival. Unique elements include ground-splitting fireworks, which explode on the ground, and taiko drum performances not featured in the Main Festival. Held at Nagara River Park, spectators can sit on the levee slopes to enjoy a wide view of the festival. Despite being a tourism event, the energy and dedication of the naked men carrying the mikoshi rival that of the Main Festival. * '''Date:''' Second Sunday of August each year * '''Location:''' {{ill|Nagara River Park|ja|長良川公園|12=draft|12=draft}} * '''Access:''' From JR {{ill|Gifu Station|ja|岐阜駅|12=draft|12=draft}} or {{ill|Meitetsu Gifu Station|ja|名鉄岐阜駅|12=draft|12=draft}}, take a {{ill|Gifu Bus|ja|岐阜乗合自動車|12=draft|12=draft}} heading to "Takami" or "Sandado Danchi" (approx. 20 minutes). Get off at "Ukaiya" and walk 3 minutes.
== References == {{Reflist}} == See Also == * {{ill|Tejikarao Shrine|ja|手力雄神社 (岐阜市)|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Fire festival|ja|火祭り|12=draft|12=draft}}
